  <h2>I. Getting started with HTML</h2>


    <h3><span><b>The World Wide Web</b></span></h3>
      <div class="contentblock">
        <p>The web needs three components:</p>
  <ol>
    <li> <em>client</em> (computer or browser),</li>
    <li> <em>Internet</em> and</li>
    <li> <em>servers</em>.</li>
  </ol>
        <p> A client opens his web browser and types in for example www.facebook.com.
      The browser sends this http <em>(Hypertext Transfer Protocol)</em> request
      to a server which sends back the correct HTML document. The browser can interpret
      the HTML document and display the information.
        </p>
      </div>

    <h3><span><b>HTML</b></span></h3>
      <div class="flexdisplay">
      <div class="htmlimage"><img src="imagehtml.png" alt="HTML" height="80" width="190"></div>
      <div class="contentblock">
      HTML <em>(HyperText Markup Language)</em> is a language the browser uses
      to <em>interpret web pages</em> and the basic building block of the Web.
      It defines and depicts a webpage's content. Two other important technologies
      next to HTML are <em>CSS (Webpage's appearance/presentation)</em> and
      <em>JavaScript(functionality/behavior)</em>.
      </div>
      </div>

    <h3><span><b>HTML elements and attributes</b></span></h3>
      <div class="contentblock">
        <p>A web browser displays the <b>HTML elements</b> we give him. Most tags contain
        an opening <em>tag</em>, some content and a closing tag. There are also tags,
      which don't have a closing tag e.g. "br" (break).
        </p>

        <p>There are elements which can contain additional values named <b>attributes</b>
      in their opening tags. These attributes give additional information to the browser.
      The image tag for example uses the attribute "src", the value "url" (path or local
      computer file). If the image can't be shown, the "alt" attribute value "text" is shown.
        </p>
      </div>
    <h3><span><b>Useful HTML Tags</b></span></h3>

      <div class="flexdisplay">
      <div class="contentblock">
        <p>There are thousands of tags, that can be used for writing in HTML.
        A long list on HTML tags can be found  <a href="https://www.w3schools.com/tags/">here.</a>
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="htmlimage"><img src="imagetaglist.png" alt="Taglist" height="210" width="350"></div>
      </div>

    <h3><span><b>Why do we say, that computers are stupid?</b></span></h3>
      <div class="contentblock">
        <p>Computers can only display what they read, <span>but they're not able to do</span> abstract
       thinking. Therefore it's important to write correct codes to avoid problems in a program.
        </p>
      </div>

    <h3><span><b>Inline and Box elements</b></span></h3>
      <div class="contentblock">
        <p><b> Inline</b> elements describe tags, that will be interpreted by the browser as one line.
       In contrary, <b>box</b> elements build an "invisible" box around the content, whereby a line break
       will be created.
        </p>
      </div>

    <h3><span><b>Document structure</b></span></h3>
      <div class="contentblock">
       Following a document structure is important for other developers to read quickly your
       written code and having a structure for yourself. The document should start with an <em>DOCTYPE HTML</em> tag,
       to describe the type of document you're using. Afterwards an <em>html</em> tag surrounds the
       whole document. It can be followed by a <em>head</em> tag including meta data, also important
       when working with JavaScript. The style CSS-concepts can also be included in the head section.
       It is followed by a <em>title</em>, shown on the top of the document and a <em>body</em> section,
       containing the content of the website. Within the body section we can use p-Tags, h1-Tags etc.
       to fill in the content. However, it's important to use indentation, the indentation level
       should increase when an idea starts and decrease when an idea is finished.
      </div>
       <p style="text-align:center;"><img src="documentstructure.png" alt="Document structure" height="350" width="550"></p>

    <br>
    <br>

