  <h2>II. Adding CSS for Style</h2>

    <h3><span><b>Understanding CSS </b></span></h3>

      <div class="contentblock">
        <p><b>CSS</b> means <em>"most specific rule applied"</em> and describes how the element will be displayed. In CSS you
        first write a selector e.g. p (Paragraph), class (attributes) etc. and then define what style. To understand the concept better
        feel free to have a look at  <a href="https://css-tricks.com/how-css-selectors-work/"> the following website</a>. Moreover,
        you can use spans, divs, ids etc. to add more style to your webpage. This is explained in <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mpyJ28dkzrU">the following video</a>.
      </div>
      <div class="video"><p style="text-align:center;"><iframe width="610" height="410" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/mpyJ28dkzrU?"></iframe></p>
      </div>

    <h3><span><b>Understanding the importance of style</b></span></h3>

      <div class="contentblock">
        <p>To understand the importance of CSS style, have a look at the <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sLo3N7YjZbU">following video</a>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="video">
        <p style="text-align:center;"><iframe width="610" height="410" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/sLo3N7YjZbU"></iframe></p>
      </div>

    <h3><span><b>Understanding the box model</b></span></h3>
      <div class="contentblock">
        <p>As described before is <b>everything on a webpage divided into boxes</b>. As you can see on
        <a href="http://assignments.udacity-extras.appspot.com/courses/html-css/samples/box-model.html">
        this webpage assignment</a> the box model is describes in four parts. The <em>content</em> in the middle contains
        the main text, images etc. Around it we can find the <em>paddle</em> which can be described as the background behind the text. The <em>border</em>
        is defined as the corder around the whole text. The <em>margin</em> sets the space around the textarea.
        </p>

        <p>The <em>size</em> of boxes, texts etc. can be set in <em>pixels or in percentages</em>. Percentages help to make the box shrink or grow
        depending on the size of the screen and therefore create a better user experience. It can also be set a <em>max width</em> to make sure it
        only grows only up to a certain size. Moreover, the box-sizing attribute added to the border-box helps to deal with sizing problems.
        </p>
      </div>


    <h3><span><b>Dive deeper into box positioning</b></span></h3>
      <div class="contentblock">
        <p> Divs are by nature <em>block elements</em> and therefore <em>take up the entire width of a page</em>. By adding the rule display:flex to the suited
        CSS, the behaviour will be overwritten and both elements appear next to each other.
        </p>
      </div>

    <h3><span><b>Semantic tags</b></span></h3>
      <div class="flexdisplay">
      <div class="contentblock">
        <p>Another option to add style to a webpage is using <b>semantic tags</b> <em>as e.g. h1, h2, title etc.</em> which also use styles. For more
        information please have a look <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element#Content_sectioning">here</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="htmlimage"><img src="imagesemantictag.png" alt="Semantictag" height="210" width="350"></div>
      </div>


    <h3><span><b>Why does style matter a lot?</b></span></h3>
      <div class="contentblock"> It matters a lot where the rules are defined and in what order they are applied. The following list describes the <em>order in which
      rules are applied</em>:
      <ol>
        <li> Default browser style</li>
        <li> Stylesheet in a separate file </li>
        <li> Inside HTML stylesheet (should only be used for small projects)</li>
        <li> Inline style in an element (should be avoided, as mistakes can occure easily)</li>
    </ol>
      </div>
    <h3><span><b> How to create a nicely designed webpage?</b></span></h3>
      <div class="contentblock">
        <div><label class='input-label'><input class='input-toggle' type='checkbox' checked> Look for natural boxes</label></div>
        <div><label class='input-label'><input class='input-toggle' type='checkbox' checked> Look if there are any repeated styles and semantic elements</label></div>
        <div><label class='input-label'><input class='input-toggle' type='checkbox' checked> Write your own HTML down</label></div>
        <div><label class='input-label'><input class='input-toggle' type='checkbox' checked> Apply styles with CSS</label></div>
        <div><label class='input-label'><input class='input-toggle' type='checkbox' checked> Fix mistakes</label></div>
      </div>
    <h3><span><b> How to check your HTML to make sure it'll look nice in different browsers?</b></span></h3>
      <div class="contentblock">
        <p> <a href="http://validator.w3.org/#validate_by_input">This website</a> offers a free service to check the final HTML.
        </p>
        <p> <a href="http://jigsaw.w3.org/css-validator/#validate_by_input">This website</a> offers a free service to check the final CSS.
        </p>
      </div>
